[19.335501, "o", "ery ERROR line by type (e.g. timeout, connection refused, out\u001b[23;1H\u001b[2K  of memory, permission denied) and give me a per-category count plus the noisiest file. Use your chunk → map\u001b[24;1H\u001b[2K  → reduce playbook: enumerate the files, fan out a batched query$llm to classify, then aggregate the\u001b[25;1H\u001b[2K  structured results in a clojure fence. Inline a short chunk plan (files scanned, batches, sub-model) in your\u001b[26;1H\u001b[2K  answer.\u001b[0m\u001b[27;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m[\u001b[0m\u001b[1;96m+\u001b[0m\u001b[2m] \u001b[0m\u001b[1;97mIteration 1 / 100\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(27858 tok)\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(9.5s)\u001b[0m\u001b[28;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m  Think: \u001b[0m\u001b[2mIteration 1, no history. I need to enumerate the files under logs/ first, count ERROR lines, and \u001b[0m\u001b[29;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2massess scale. Let me find the log files, count them, total ERROR lines, and sizes. I'll grep ERROR \u001b[0m\u001b[30;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2mlines so I can chunk them efficiently rather than feeding entire files. Using bash for enumeration.\u001b[0m\u001b[31;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m[\u001b[0m\u001b[1;93m⠙\u001b[0m\u001b[2m]\u001b[0m \u001b[96mCalculating...\u001b[0m\u001b[2m (9.4s)\u001b[0m"]
